{{Infobox scientist | name = Charlene Polio | image = File:Charlene Polio.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|01|14|df=y}} | birth_place = [[New Haven, Connecticut]], [[The United States]] | residence = [[East Lansing, Michigan]], [[The United States]] | fields = {{plainlist | * [[Second language acquisition]] * [[Second language writing]] }} | workplaces = {{plainlist | * [[Michigan State University]] }} | alma_mater = [[University of Pennsylvania]], [[UCLA]] | doctoral_advisor = | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | known_for = {{plainlist | * [[Second language writing]] }} | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | awards = | spouse = | children = {{URL|https://www.rand.org/about/people/h/heins_sara.html|Sara Heins}} }}
'''Charlene Polio''' (born 1961) is a Professor and Associate chair in the Department of Linguistics and Germanic, Slavic, Asian and African Languages at the [[Michigan State University]], [[The United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polio.msu.domains/|title=Michigan State University|date=3 October 2018|publisher=Polio.msu.domains}}</ref> Her research focuses on [[second language acquisition]] with a special focus on [[second language writing]]. Along with [[Alister Cumming|Cumming]], [[Ken Hyland|Hyland]], [[Judit Kormos|Kormos]], [[Paul Kei Matsuda|Matsuda]], [[Rosa Manchón|Manchón]], [[Lourdes Ortega|Ortega]], [[Neomy Storch|Storch]] and [[Marjolijn Verspoor|Verspoor]], Polio is considered as one of the most prominent researchers on second language writing.{{By whom|date=October 2018}}
== Career == Polio obtained her [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[Linguistics]] in 1983 and her her [[Master of Arts]] degree in [[Teaching English to speakers of other languages|TESOL]] in 1984 at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. In 1992 she obtained her [[PhD]] in [[Applied linguistics]] at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polio.msu.domains/education/|title=Polio - Education|date=3 October 2018|publisher=Polio.msu.domains}}</ref>
Polio was the co-editor of [[The Modern Language Journal|T''he Modern Language Journal'']]''.'' She is co-editor of [[TESOL Quarterly|''TESOL Quarterly'']] along with Peter De Costa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tesol.org/read-and-publish/journals/tesol-quarterly|title=TESOL Quarterly Editorial Board|date=3 October 2018|publisher=Tesol.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/page/journal/15457249/homepage/editorialboard.html|title=TESOL Quarterly Editorial Board|date=3 October 2018|publisher=Onlinelibrary.wiley.org}}</ref>
Since April 2018 she has been a member-at-large of the [[American Association for Applied Linguistics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aaal.org/members/charlene-polio|title=Charlene Polio - American Association for Applied Linguistics|date=3 October 2018|publisher=Aaal.org}}</ref>
==Research== Polio's research focuses on second language writing with a special focus on [[language complexity]]. She is noted for her research synthesis on accuracy measures, published in [[Language Learning (journal)|Language Learning]] in 1997. She identified three different types of accuracy measures: (1) holistic scores, (2) error-free units, and (3) error counts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/0023-8333.31997003|title=Charlene Polio (1997). Measures of Linguistic Accuracy in Second Language Writing Research|date=3 October 2018|publisher=Onlinelibrary.wiley.org}}</ref>
